result.text:
About 1.5 years ago, I started https://t.co/wGE5uFmOWu as a fun side project to help me book better award flights with my points. To my surprise, it grew much faster than I ever expected, and ended up becoming my full-time job.

As the year ends, we just hit $1.5M in ARR and now serve over a million pageviews per month. We are entirely bootstrapped, have no full-time employees besides myself, and have become very familiar with the Delaware courts.

On the technical side, I've had to solve some pretty interesting challenges to keep up with the growth. We pushed traditional PostgreSQL to its breaking point and had to move to Amazon Aurora to support our workload of over several thousand queries per second. We store over a billion rows of flight availability and history, probably the largest dataset for award travel that exists today.

Super excited for what's next ‚Äî we are working on some really cool tools to further help everyone make better use of miles and points. Feel free to reach out if you are interested in this space!

result.text:
I see very often people accusing others of copying.

The truth is, we all take inspiration from each other's.

And that's ok, and even better for softwares in general: competition forces innovation.

It's thanks to competition that we use good SaaS today. 
As long as two softwares aren't cloning and have a differentiator (not the same UI/UX, same features, and same pricing..) then someone would rather use one than the other one.

Schedulers exist for years, I remember I used Hootsuite 10 years ago. 
Jack wasn't the first, 
Tibo wasn't the first, 
Joel want the first,

But we don't care who is the first actually
Use both of them, you will have a different experience. 
And that's the best we can wish as a user: get the choice, matching our needs.

This is what has confused me about being obsessed with MRR/churn. 

People will naturally churn (unless you have a product that people wanna pay monthly for the rest of their lives) 

The goal should be extracting the most LTV out of each customer you can. 

Adam from tailwind talked about this on a podcast.

result.text:
in the last few weeks ive been still ontop of tackling CHURN for @postbridge_ and the biggest thing ive learned is how much it helps with my mental health knowing who my product is for and who it is not for

the more interviews i do the more clear it is who my ICP is and the less i worry overall when someone isnt in love with my product, cause many times its just not built for them 100% as it is for others

for many people its perfect as is! and i am going to keep improving it for those people, but i dont need to stress about pleasing every single person (though i do stress about making sure im making sure they are not my ICP, cause sometimes i DO NEED to add a feature for them!)

hope this is helpful for anyone thinking about why they should figure out who they are targeting in their business [ who is your ICP? ]
